{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01DuB1x1i729QiHawDAhKhj7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to write a test plan for specific behaviors in a REST API that does vector search and LLM re-ranking. I need to analyze each behavior and determine the minimum test level needed to catch real failures.\n\nLet me work through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Embedding vector dimensionality\n\"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.\"\n\nThis is testing that when you embed a query, it produces the right number of dimensions. \n\nMOCK-MISS: Could I mock the embedding model and still catch this? Actually, the issue here is that the embedding model might produce dimension D, but the vector DB is expecting dimension D'. This mismatch would only be caught if:\n- Either I test the actual embedding model against the actual DB schema\n- Or I test that the code validates dimensionality correctly\n\nIf I just mock the embedding model to return a vector of the right dimension, I might miss a real failure where the actual model produces a different dimension. So this seems like it needs a real embedding model call or at least the real vector DB index metadata.\n\nBut wait - the real failure is: \"embedding model produces vector of dimension X, but vector DB expects dimension Y\". To catch this:\n- I could mock the embedding model to return wrong dimension, then test that validation catches it (Unit/Integration)\n- OR I could use the real embedding model and real DB index (System/Agentic)\n\nActually, the core thing being tested is: \"does the embedding vector have the right dimensionality?\" The failure is if it doesn't match the DB. \n\nIf I use a real embedding model (which is Agentic - it's an LLM-dependent call), I'd call it and check the dimension. But the failure isn't \"the embedding is non-deterministic\" - the failure is \"the dimension is wrong\". That's deterministic.\n\nHowever, embedding models ARE deterministic in terms of output dimension - they always produce the same dimension. So I could:\n\n\n1. Call the real embedding API once (Agentic level)\n2. Verify the dimension matches the DB schema\n\nOR I could:\n1. Mock the embedding API (Integration level)\n2. Test that the code validates the dimension\n\nThe real failure scenarios matter here. If the embedding model gets upgraded from 384 to 768 dimensions but the vector DB isn't updated, that's a deployment failure I'd catch with the real API. Alternatively, if the code hardcodes a dimension that doesn't match the actual DB schema, I need the real DB metadata to validate against. Either way, I'm checking that the actual dimension produced aligns with what the system expects.\n\nThe minimum viable approach seems to be Integration level—mocking the embedding model with a known dimension while connecting to the real DB schema. This catches mismatches between code assumptions and actual infrastructure without requiring the real embedding API. But if the embedding model itself changes, only calling the real API would surface that. The core failures I'm trying to prevent are: the model producing unexpected dimensions, the code failing to validate, or the DB schema being out of sync. Unit tests handle validation logic, Integration tests handle the DB consistency piece, and only Agentic tests would catch actual model changes.\n\nThe real question is whether \"correct dimensionality\" means matching what the DB expects or matching what the actual embedding API returns. If it's the latter, I need the real model—making Agentic the minimum. Embedding models get updated, API responses can change, and the model name might resolve to something unexpected. So Agentic is probably the answer, assuming the test needs to verify the real embedding service actually produces compatible output.\n\nFor behavior 1, the embedding dimension is deterministic from the model itself, but since we're calling an external API, I'd weight it: Unit at 0.1 (just validate the logic), Integration at 0.2 (real DB schema + mock embedder), System at 0.2 (real DB + mock embedder), and Agentic at 0.5 (call the actual embedding model to confirm the dimension matches).\n\nBehavior 2 tests whether vector DB search results are properly ranked by cosine similarity score.\n\nA mock vector DB could return results in the correct order and pass the test without actually verifying the real database sorts correctly. The vector DB is likely a real external service requiring network calls, so I need at least an Integration test: a real or in-memory vector DB instance where I can query and verify the ordering actually reflects similarity scores, catching cases where the DB returns results in insertion order instead.\n\nSystem testing would only be necessary if the vector DB runs as a subprocess requiring OS-level interaction, but Integration should be sufficient. My confidence distribution: Integration dominates at 0.75, with smaller portions for System (0.1 if subprocess-based), Unit (0.05), Agentic (0.05), and Workflow (0.05).\n\nFor the LLM re-ranking behavior, I'm checking whether the re-ranker actually modifies the result order based on semantic understanding of nuanced queries. The test fails if the LLM returns the same order as the input or consistently misses the intent. This clearly depends on the LLM—whether it's a real API call or a mock matters significantly for catching actual re-ranking failures.\n\nUsing a mock that returns a different order would make the test pass without verifying the real model can understand nuanced intent, so that approach masks real problems. I need the actual LLM API to test with queries containing subtle intent and confirm the rankings differ from raw similarity results. This pushes the test toward Agentic: Unit (0.05), Integration (0.1 for fixed LLM responses), System (0.1 for subprocess-based LLM), and Agentic (0.7 since real semantic understanding is what matters).\n\nFor the empty result set behavior, the vector database is real infrastructure that needs testing against actual data. Mocking the DB to return empty sets would pass the test without confirming the real database actually filters low-relevance results instead of returning them. I need a genuine or test vector DB with data where certain queries have no close matches, then verify the search returns nothing rather than noise. This requires at minimum an Integration test with a real or test vector DB and specific data patterns.\n\nFor latency testing, the entire pipeline must run with real network calls to the embedding API, vector DB, and LLM API to measure actual end-to-end performance against the 2-second SLA.\n\nMocks won't work here since they have near-zero latency and can't reveal real bottlenecks. The test depends on actual service latencies, which are non-deterministic. To catch genuine latency failures, I need to exercise the real services in sequence. This could be **Agentic** if calling one embedding API, vector DB, and LLM in order, or **System** if running the full pipeline through the REST API with real HTTP calls. The measurement itself is deterministic, but the underlying services introduce variability. ** services, which makes it a **System** test since we need the real HTTP layer to measure end-to-end latency.\n\nThe key insight is that \"receiving the query to returning re-ranked results\" encompasses the full request/response cycle through the REST API. Real HTTP calls combined with real external services (embedding, vector DB, LLM) define a System-level test. I'd allocate roughly 65% to System tests, with smaller portions for Agentic (20%) if testing just the Python component latency, Integration (5%), Unit (2%), and Workflow (8%).\n\nNow checking if my test descriptions align with the minimum levels I assigned: behavior 1 requires calling the real embedding API to verify dimensions—that's Agentic. Behavior 2 needs querying a real or test vector DB to check ordering—Integration level. Behavior 3 calls the real LLM to confirm it reorders results—Agentic. Behavior 4 tests the vector DB with no-match data—Integration. Behavior 5 sends actual HTTP requests through the REST endpoint, which is System-level. Each test description matches its corresponding minimum level.\n\nFor behavior 1, I'm reconsidering what failure modes matter. The embedding model could output wrong dimensions, the code might skip validation, or the DB schema could be misaligned. A mocked embedding with real DB schema catches validation and schema issues but misses if the actual embedding service produces unexpected dimensions. Using the real embedding model against the real DB schema catches all three failure modes, making Agentic the safer choice here.\n\nFor behavior 3, the critical test is whether the LLM actually understands nuanced queries and reorders results accordingly. Real failures would be the re-ranking step being completely broken or the LLM failing to grasp subtle intent differences.\n\nA mock could simulate different ordering, but that only validates the plumbing works—not whether the real LLM comprehends nuance. Since the behavior explicitly requires nuanced understanding, I need the actual model to verify this works correctly.\n\nFor behavior 5, the latency requirement depends on whether we're measuring against real infrastructure or if we can simulate it. The median case suggests we need actual system performance data, not theoretical estimates. receiving it at the Python function level, not the HTTP layer. In that case, Agentic might be sufficient.\n\nSystem feels like the safer choice here. \"End-to-end\" typically implies the full HTTP round-trip, the REST API itself is part of what we're testing, and HTTP overhead can be meaningful. Going with System.\n\nFor behavior 1, I should reconsider whether we actually need real embedding calls or if Integration would work. The core question is whether mocking the embedding model is acceptable. Real API calls catch unexpected dimension changes or format shifts from model updates, but we could also stub the embedding to return the correct shape and verify the downstream integration works. Integration might be sufficient if we're primarily concerned with the vector DB compatibility rather than the embedding service itself.\n\nHowever, there's a distinction between two failure modes: the code not validating dimensions correctly (Integration can catch this with a mock), versus the embedding model actually producing wrong dimensions (requires Agentic). Since both are real risks—especially model upgrades—Agentic is the minimum level needed to catch both scenarios.\n\nThe core issue is that mocking the embedding model lets us test validation logic, but it masks whether the real model's output actually matches the database schema. Using the real embedding model ensures we're verifying the actual invariant: that produced vectors have the correct dimensionality for the index. correct\" output. If we define \"correct\" as \"matches the DB\", then we could assume the embedding API produces dimension D (which we know from documentation), check the DB schema is set to dimension D, and assert they match—that would be Integration level testing of the configuration rather than the actual API.\n\nThe real question is whether we're validating that the embedding model itself produces the right dimension, or just that the code is configured to handle whatever dimension it produces. The behavior seems to require both: verifying the actual vector output from the real embedding API and ensuring the DB configuration aligns with it. That points toward Agentic testing as the primary concern, with Integration as a secondary consideration.\n\nLet me reconsider the test levels more carefully. Unit tests cover isolated functions with no I/O. Integration tests wire multiple modules together using local databases or filesystems. System tests involve subprocesses, OS calls, or real external APIs. Agentic tests require real LLM non-determinism or actual model calls. Workflow tests chain multiple agentic steps together.\n\nFor this behavior, calling the embedding API is a System-level concern since it's a real external API call. Checking the DB schema is Integration. The combination leans System overall. But whether embedding API calls themselves count as System or Agentic depends on whether they involve model non-determinism—embedding models are typically deterministic, so they'd be System rather than Agentic.\n\nLet me map out the behaviors:\n- Behavior 1: embedding API + DB schema = System minimum\n- Behavior 2: vector DB search = Integration minimum (if local)\n- Behavior 3: LLM re-ranking + vector DB = Agentic minimum\n- Behavior 4: vector DB search = Integration minimum (if local)\n- Behavior 5: full latency test = System minimum\n\nFor behavior 2 specifically, testing that similarity search returns results in descending cosine similarity order requires verifying the vector DB actually returns them sorted correctly. I could mock the vector DB to test this, or I could use a real local vector DB instance to verify the actual ordering behavior. Unit by testing dimension validation logic. Integration testing with a mocked embedding and real DB schema could also catch it. But the real embedding model producing incorrect dimensions is something only Agentic testing would reliably surface.\n\nFor similarity search order, Unit tests might verify the sorting logic works, but Integration is where I'd actually confirm the database returns results in the expected order. System testing becomes relevant if the database is remote or runs as a subprocess.\n\nThe LLM re-ranking behavior could be tested at Unit or Integration levels with fixed responses, though Agentic testing is needed to validate how the real model actually understands and re-ranks the results. System testing might be necessary depending on whether the LLM is local or remote.\n\nEmpty result sets can be validated at Unit by testing filter logic, but Integration testing with actual database queries is more reliable. System testing matters if the database is remote.\n\nFor latency SLAs, System testing is critical for real HTTP calls, and Agentic testing is needed for actual embedding and LLM latencies. Integration testing with a local database could provide some signal.\n\nThe test descriptions capture the key validation points: Behavior 1 verifies embedding dimensionality against the vector DB schema using real APIs. Behavior 2 confirms similarity-based ordering with known vectors in a test database. Behavior 3 ensures the LLM re-ranker produces semantically different rankings than raw similarity. Behavior 4 validates that the filtering threshold prevents low-similarity results from being returned. Behavior 5 measures end-to-end latency across real embedding, database, and LLM calls to ensure the 2-second SLA is met.\n\nNow checking alignment between minimum_level and test requirements: each test's minimum_level matches what it actually exercises—Agentic tests call real embedding or LLM APIs, Integration tests use local test databases, and the System test makes real HTTP requests with full stack latency measurement.\n\nFor plan_consistent, I need to verify each test's minimum_level is both necessary and sufficient. Behavior 1 requires Agentic because embedding is a real model call. Behavior 2 needs Integration since it wires multiple modules with a local test DB. Behavior 3 requires Agentic due to real LLM non-determinism in the re-ranker. Behavior 4 stays at Integration—it's testing database filtering logic without external model calls. Behavior 5 demands System level because it measures real HTTP latency across all components.\n\nNow assigning level_probabilities. Embedding dimensionality is most likely Agentic (0.55) since catching dimension mismatches requires the real embedding API, though some validation could happen at Unit (0.10) or Integration (0.20). Similarity search order is predominantly Integration (0.75) because it needs a real or test vector database to verify sort behavior correctly.\n\nLLM re-ranking depends heavily on Agentic testing (0.70) to validate semantic understanding, though mocked responses could cover some Integration scenarios (0.10). Empty result sets also lean Integration (0.75) to test filtering against specific data patterns. Latency SLA is primarily System-level (0.60) since it requires actual HTTP calls and live services, with Agentic contributing (0.25) due to real embedding and LLM latency factors.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13326,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13326},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"45934aff-3d2d-4b4e-a368-1106a229ed4b","uuid":"4961d04e-f366-43a0-aedc-55a8f275f617"}
